  "prompt": "What universities does Immune Design recruit new grads from? What majors are they looking for?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, **Immune Design** (a biotechnology company focused on immunotherapy) typically recruits new graduates from top universities with strong life sciences, bioengineering, and related programs. While they don\u2019t publicly disclose a specific list of universities, they likely target institutions with renowned programs in biology, immunology, bioengineering, and related fields. Some examples of universities they might recruit from include:\n\n- **Stanford University**\n- **University of California, Berkeley**\n- **Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)**\n- **Harvard University**\n- **University of Washington**\n- **California Institute of Technology (Caltech)**\n- **Johns Hopkins University**\n- **University of California, San Francisco (UCSF)**\n- **University of Pennsylvania**\n- **University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA)**\n\n### Majors They Look For:\nImmune Design typically seeks candidates with backgrounds in:\n- **Biology**\n- **Immunology**\n- **Biochemistry**\n- **Bioengineering**\n- **Molecular Biology**\n- **Biotechnology**\n- **Chemical Engineering**\n- **Pharmaceutical Sciences**\n- **Data Science/Bioinformatics** (for computational roles)\n\n### Skills and Experience:\nCandidates are often expected to have:\n- Strong foundational knowledge in immunology, cancer biology, or infectious diseases.\n- Lab skills, such as cell culture, molecular biology techniques, or assay development.\n- Experience with bioinformatics, data analysis, or computational modeling (for certain roles).\n- Collaborative and innovative problem-solving abilities.\n\nFor the most accurate and up-to-date information, I recommend checking **Immune Design's career page** or reaching out to their HR department directly.",
